<div type="definition">
<p>LACK MUTUALLY DIFFERENT PARTS OR FEATURES.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current word for unadorned simplicity is pǔ 樸 (ant. lì 麗 "beautifully patterned").</p>
<p>2. Sù 素 (ant. huá 華 "elaborate") means basically "pristine white" and refers to an original state of pristine plain simplicity of things.</p>
<p>3. Zhì 質 (ant. wén 文 ) focusses on what is real, fundamental and basic rather than what are external temporary adornment.</p>
<p>4. Jiǎn 簡 (ant. fán 繁 ) focuses on lack of inner complexity or multifariousness of any kind.</p>
        </div>
